                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>How did Jeff make it work?</h2>
                    <p>
                      <b>Rule 1</b>: Create, don't consume.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Prefer tools like google docs, google sheets, and <a target='_blank' href='https://scratch.mit.edu/'>Scratch</a> to tools like <a target='_blank' href='https://newsela.com/'>NewsELA</a> or <a target='_blank' href='https://www.flocabulary.com/'>Flocabulary</a>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <b>Rule 2</b>: Don't use blocking/monitoring software.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Please ask me as much about this as you want. Briefly, this software teaches kids nothing. You want kids to be able to use computers productively in your classroom,
                      and also in their highschool, college, and professional lives. You should start teaching them how to regulate their own online behavior now. You don't spend 1hr straight working on a computer
                      without taking an occasional break to check Facebook or message your friends, but you figure out how to do that and get your work done. Teach this to kids.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <b>Rule 3</b>: Computer time is instructional time.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Your lesson might be around learning how to summarize the main idea of a passage, and little Teddy might be sending innappropriate emails to his classmates, and little Lisa might be looking up pictures of lolcatz, or worse. This is now your lesson.
                      How do you address it?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <b>Rule 4</b>: Make it fun.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Kids have fun with technology outside of school. If you make it dull inside school, they'll look for other, potentially more destructive ways to have fun.
                      Let them message and email eachother. Let them Google something they're curious about. Bring in fun stuff, like speakers, cameras, and any other technology you use in your life. Let kids explore with it.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <b>Rule 5</b>: On open ended assignments, use lots of examples and a very clear rubric.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      If you try an open ended assignment, <a target='_blank' href='https://docs.google.com/document/d/13lz88oVniPoMI6epgQCOp7lh3CyAWAJRopEBuZR5kKM/edit?usp=sharing'>like this one</a>, make a rubric and make an example(s) ahead of time.
                      If scoring on a 4 point scale, make examples of 1, 2, 3, and 4 level work, and share those examples with the class. <a target='_blank' href='https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JhceqXFS2n59RkZnP7ToZOFCYrF2WoEN1EyB_dRMBnY/edit?usp=sharing
                      of a "twitter feed" from that project.'>Here is an example</a> of a twitter feed from that project.
                    </p>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->
