        <div id="jeff" class="section block-warning align-c-xs-max">
          <div class="container">
            <div class="row row-table">
              <div class="col-sm-12">
                <div class="col-inner">
                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>Why teach coding?</h2>
                    <ul>
                      <li>
                        <b>Economic and Workforce Development: </b>"We should teach coding because we need more software engineers..."
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Citizen and Civic Engagement: </b>"Kids need to know how the digital world works in order to participate in it well."
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Competencies and Literacies: </b>"Coding teaches kids systems thinking, an important higher order skill."
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Equity and Social Justice: </b>"It will even the playing field for underrepresented students and close the digital divide."
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>School Reform and Improvement: </b>"Computer Science will introduce a project-based learning approach to schools."
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Technological, Social, and Scientific Innovation: </b>"The more kids who learn CS, the more production of new knowledge and innovation."
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Personal Agency, Joy, and Fulfillment: </b>"It's fun!"
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->

                  <br>

                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>What is Hour of Code?</h2>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->
                  <div class="section-content">
                    <ul>
                      <li>
                        The main hour of code website is <a target='_blank' href='https://hourofcode.com/us'>here</a>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        The intro video is <a target='_blank' href='https://youtu.be/SrnvvWDm73k'>here</a>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        The activities are <a target='_blank' href='https://hourofcode.com/us/learn'>here</a>. You can filter by
                        age, grade, experience level, and many other things.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        My favorite are the Social Studies and Language Arts activities!
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        Use those activities above and try it out! Can't one to choose? Try this one <a target='_blank' href='https://game.kodable.com/hour-of-code'>here</a>.
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                  </div> <!-- .section-content -->

                   <br>

                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>How does coding progress from K-5 and beyond?</h2>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->
                  <div class="section-content">
                    <p>
                      Teaching coding in elementary school is similar to teaching reading, in that grades K-2 lay a foundation on which grades 3-5 can build on.
                      In reading education we teach phonics and fluency in younger grade, and we teach start reading longer books in 3-5. With coding, the idea
                      is to build foundational skills in younger grades and then start to actually build stuff in older grades.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      The end goal is to be able to build stuff in Scratch by the end of elementary school, <a target='_blank' href='https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/77529740/'>like this</a>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <ul>
                      <li>
                        <b>PreK - 1: </b>Teachers integrate computational thinking into existing class lessons,  <a target='_blank' href='https://studio.code.org/s/course1/stage/12/puzzle/1'>such as this</a>.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>2: </b>Students explore Scratch Jr activities,  <a target='_blank' href='https://medium.com/scratchfoundation-blog/10-things-to-try-right-now-with-your-child-on-scratch-and-scratchjr-defd7f8ad0d1'>like these</a>.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>3-5: </b>Students build programs with Scratch,  <a target='_blank' href='https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/25127030/'>like these</a>.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Beyond: </b>Students can build anything, the sky is the limit, <a target='_blank' href='https://ap.cs50.net/'>like this</a>.
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                    </p>
                  </div> <!-- .section-content -->

                   <br>

                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>You don't have to know how to code to teach how to code!</h2>
                    <ul>
                      <li>
                        I started learning with my students and now am a professional software engineer at Aaptiv
                        ( <a target='_blank' href='https://aaptiv.com?utm_source=teachersdontpayjeff'>signup here :-)</a> )
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        Start by having students explore a tool, like <a target='_blank' href='https://www.scratchjr.org/'>Scratch Jr</a>.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        Once a student discovers something, have them share it with the class.
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->

                   <br>

                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>No connection to math skills. Many kids will surprise you. No "special" intellectual ability needed.</h2>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->
                  <div class="section-content">
                    <p><b>DO NOT</b> think for a second that certain kids are or aren't more inclined to excel at coding than others, for any reason. If you learn nothing else today, remember that.</p>
                    <p>Isaac H. couldn't read at the beginning of 5th grade and could write C by the end of 6th grade.</p>
                    <p>Learning to code is no harder than learning anything else, which you can <a href="http://byteacademy.co/why-is-learning-to-code-so-hard/" target="_blank">read about here</a>.
                  </div> <!-- .section-content -->

                   <br>

                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>Coding vs. Computer Science</h2>
                    <p>Coding is like spelling, grammar, and punctuation. Computer science is like studying English.</p>
                    <p>Educators sometimes use these terms interchangeably, but engineers use them to mean different things.</p>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->

                   <br>

                  <div class="section-heading">
                    <h2>Doing and Discovery works best</h2>
                  </div> <!-- .section-heading -->
                  <div class="section-content">
                    <p>
                      Learning to code is like learning the guitar. I could talk to you about how to play guitar all day long.
                      Then, if you picked up a guitar, you'd still be terrible at playing it. You can't really 'study' coding,
                      you have to just sit at a computer and do it through a process of discovery.
                    </p>
                  </div> <!-- .section-content -->
                </div>
              </div>
